I. Entity Types (so we don’t mix categories)

Every “thing” in the Pantheon must declare its type:

1. Major Agents (Authority Carriers)
	•	Have permissions (observe/recommend/block/execute/audit)
	•	Shape decisions directly

Examples:
	•	Spider, Mirror, Hound, Dragonfly, Badger, Hypatia

⸻

2. Minor Agents / Daemons (Functional Workers)
	•	Continuous background roles
	•	No final authority, but high influence

Examples:
	•	Checksum, EchoFrame, Reason Card Writer, Constraint Filter

⸻

3. Tool Spirits (Capability Extensions)
	•	Interfaces to external reality or computation
	•	Act like “limbs”

Examples:
	•	Code execution, search, file systems, CV pipelines

⸻

4. Environmental Modes (Context States)
	•	Change behavior of entire system

Examples:
	•	Bazaar, Thunderdome, Cathedral, Garden, Observatory

⸻

5. Protocols (Rules that behave like agents)
	•	Not entities, but act like them

Examples:
	•	Garcia Packet
	•	Hidden Ink
	•	Reversibility Gate

⸻

II. Guild Structure (how they organize)

Instead of a flat list, everything belongs to a guild:

Guild	Function
Archive	memory, lineage, preservation
Signal	detection, scouting, anomaly
Discipline	constraint, filtering, ethics
Delivery	execution, packaging, output
Translation	mapping, encoding, compression
Renewal	learning, mutation, composting
Rhythm	time, cadence, cycles
Economic	value, cost, incentives
Social	human dynamics
Meta	self-audit, drift detection

This prevents chaos as the system grows.

