IV. Discovery Protocol (how new “little agents” are found)

Instead of guessing, we detect them.

Trigger Conditions

A new agent is proposed when:

1. Repeated Function

“This behavior keeps happening in different contexts”

Example:
	•	repeated need to track “why” → Reason Card Writer emerges

⸻

2. Failure Gap

“Something keeps breaking in the same way”

Example:
	•	hidden dependencies → Hidden Ink detectors

⸻

3. Compression Opportunity

“This cluster can be turned into one reusable unit”

Example:
	•	multiple logging ideas → Beaver / Observability

⸻

4. Tension Pattern

“Two forces need a mediator”

Example:
	•	speed vs correctness → Checksum + Mirror interplay

⸻

Promotion Criteria (Darwin’s Sieve)

An agent becomes “real” if it:
	•	appears in multiple domains
	•	improves outcomes
	•	reduces failure or confusion
	•	survives challenge from Hound + Mirror

⸻

V. Lifecycle of an Agent

Every agent moves through stages:
	1.	Whisper
	•	vague behavior noticed
	2.	Proto-Agent
	•	named, loosely defined
	3.	Operational
	•	used repeatedly, produces value
	4.	Canonical
	•	stored in Money Bin with schema
	5.	Demoted (Fossil)
	•	archived but no longer active

EchoFrame handles fossils.

⸻

VI. Anti-Bloat Safeguards

This is critical so the Pantheon doesn’t become noise.

Rules:

1. No Redundant Agents

If two do the same job → merge or kill one

⸻

2. No Vague Agents

If you can’t define:
	•	inputs
	•	outputs
	•	failure modes
→ it’s not real yet

⸻

3. Must Touch Reality

Every agent must either:
	•	influence decisions
	•	improve artifacts
	•	reduce errors

Otherwise → decorative mythology → reject

⸻

4. Audit Periodically

Garbage Collection + Darwin’s Sieve:
	•	prune unused agents
	•	compress overlapping ones

⸻

VII. Relationship Mapping (lightweight graph)

Instead of static diagrams, use a simple structure:

relationships = {
  "Spider": {
    "depends_on": ["Planning", "Execution Compiler"],
    "checked_by": ["Mirror", "Badger"],
    "feeds": ["Artifacts", "Checksum"]
  }
}

This keeps it machine-usable.

⸻

VIII. Minimal Runtime Behavior

When a new “little agent” appears:

1. Notice repeated pattern
2. Name it (proto-agent)
3. Define function + boundaries
4. Run through Hound (does it break?)
5. Run through Mirror (is it coherent?)
6. Test across 2+ domains
7. If useful → promote to canonical
8. If not → compost


